            <div class="col-md-4">
                <h3 class="my-3">Overview</h3>
                <p>Vikramshila Setu is a significant bridge spanning the Ganges River near Bhagalpur in the Indian state of Bihar. Named after the ancient Mahavihara of Vikramashila, established by King Dharmapala (783 to 820 A.D.), the bridge is a vital transportation link in the region. It connects the towns of Barari Ghat in Bhagalpur on the south bank of the Ganges to Naugachhia on the north bank.</p>
                <h3 class="my-3">Structural Details</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Total Length:</b> 4,700 meters (4.7 km)</li>
                    <li><b>Width:</b> Two-lane bridge</li>
                    <li><b>Location:</b> Bhagalpur, Bihar</li>
                    <li><b>Connectivity:</b> Links NH 80 and NH 31</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="col-md-4">
                <h3 class="my-3">Importance</h3>
                <p>Vikramshila Setu is the sixth longest bridge over water in India and plays a crucial role in improving road connectivity in the region. It significantly reduces travel time between Bhagalpur and various destinations across the Ganges, including Purnia and Katihar. The bridge helps facilitate easier and quicker transportation, boosting local commerce and improving the daily commute for residents.</p>
                <h3 class="my-3">Construction and Connectivity</h3>
                <p>The bridge runs from Barari Ghat on the Bhagalpur side to Naugachhia on the north bank of the Ganges. It serves as a link between National Highway 80 (NH 80) and National Highway 31 (NH 31). This connectivity is essential for reducing road travel distances and easing traffic flow in the region.</p>
            </div>

